doi = {10.1145/3707127.3707148},
abstract = {Abstract — This paper presents an automated plantar pressure monitoring system using the Internet of Things (IoT) for early detection of diabetic foot ulcers (DFU). DFUs are common complications of diabetes that can negatively impact the life of a patient. Usual treatments for DFUs are drastic as they may include amputating the area affected, which is why this study aims to create a wearable foot device with a real-time monitoring system powered by the Internet of Things (IoT) to measure the plantar pressure experienced by the user. An important aspect of the prototype of this study is that it follows the three paradigms of intelligent manufacturing systems: sensing, smart, and sustainable. There will be force-sensitive resistors (FSR) to measure the plantar pressure and an LED to alert the user if an abnormal pressure is detected. Additionally, the smart feature will be represented by the IoT system that will notify the user if the plantar pressure experienced by the user exceeds the plantar threshold of 200 kPa. This system was made possible through the use of the Arduino IoT cloud, wherein the values of the FSRs and LED status can be monitored in the dashboard in real-time. The system will also automatically notify the user using the dashboard and by the LED, which turns red once any of the FSRs senses pressure greater than the threshold. To potentially help patients prevent DFUs from occurring, the prototype is designed to be a low-cost, non-disposable, reusable, and universal product.},
